Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis

Summarise the main characteristics of a dataset in the context of a business problem, market or customer base

  • Very common analytics use case usually undertaken at the beginning of a company’s data strategy
  • Involves visual methods and statistical modelling to identify outliers, trends and patterns in the data that merits further study
  • Results generally delivered in the form of reports, slides and web pages

Example Analysis

Customer Churn Modelling

Customer Churn Modelling

Prevent customer churn by targeting customers identified as high-risk churn candidates

  • Still one of the most typical analytics use cases in many industries
    (especially in the telecommunication and energy sector)
  • Churn projects are often part of a bigger retention strategy involving related data projects such as
    • Customer profiling
    • Customer segmentation
    • Customer surveys
    • Analysis of customer service interactions

What Data is Used for the Modelling?

  • Customer “dimensions”
    Age, gender, marital status, home address, phone number
  • Customer Behaviour
    Types of services used, service frequency, spending, spending patterns, recency, service usage patterns, customer service interactions, tenure
  • Supporting datasets
    Public census data, commercial socio-economic datasets (e.g. Helix Personas), social media data

Definition of Churn

  • No clear churn definition or event due to prepaid services, low usage or seasonal usage frequencies, “tourist usage”
  • Historic services and/or business model changes
  • Not all customers are equally valueable (specific customer churn might be economically acceptable)
  • Churn “notice period” – how long in advance do we need to predict churn?

Modelling Data Set

Building a churn model requires the data in a tabular format where rows correspond to customers and rows represent customer attributes/features.

Customer ID Age Tenure Total Spend … Churn
12345 35 175 $352 … yes
12346 21 27 $52 … no
12347 43 691 $752 … no
… … … … … …

Data Preparation

Creating the modelling dataset is the most time consuming part of the project:

  • Technical challenges
    Customer behaviour is extracted from transactional data which is often huge requiring the use of big data tools
  • Security/access challenges
    Data stored in live, operation-critical DBs limiting access for analysts
  • Operational challenges
    Data preparation needs to be automated to ensure timely model refreshes

Machine Learning

Supervised Learning

Learning a function that maps an input to an output based on the example input-output pairs in the modelling dataset.

Input is the data of a customer and the output is the churn label (also often a probability of churn).

Model Building

  • Churn data is often highly imbalanced – there are fewer churners that non-churners
  • Black box models unsuitable as knowing the reason of churn is important to prevent it
  • Model building needs to be automated for timely model refreshes

Model Performance

Model Integration

How are churn model predictions used?

  • To retain customers the model needs to provide information on the reason of churn
  • Predictions need to be linked with other systems to automatically respond to high-risk customers
  • Wider team is required to effectively exploit the churn model predictions

Summary

  • Data on customer behaviour enriched with various other datasets are used to predict and prevent customer churn
  • Business domain knowledge is required to precisely define the churn event
  • Building and operationalising the model requires several technical functions of a business
  • The model needs integration with other systems to be useful
